revision.text:
In [[mathematics|mathematical]] [[set theory]], '''Baumgartner's axiom (BA)''' can be one of three different [[axiom]]s introduced by [[James Earl Baumgartner]].
An axiom introduced by {{harvtxt|Baumgartner|1973}} states that any two [[aleph-1|ℵ<sub>1</sub>]]-[[dense set|dense]] subsets of the [[real line]] are [[order-isomorphic]]. [[Stevo Todorcevic|Todorcevic]] showed that this Baumgartner's Axiom is a consequence of the [[Proper Forcing Axiom]]<ref>[https://www.math.uci.edu/node/23629 Todorcevic's proof of Baumgartner Axiom by Garrett Ervin] </ref>.
Another axiom introduced by {{harvtxt|Baumgartner|1975}} states that [[Martin's axiom]] for [[partially ordered set]]s MA<sub>''P''</sub>(''κ'') is true for all [[partially ordered set]]s ''P'' that are countable closed, well met and ℵ<sub>1</sub>-linked and all [[Cardinal number|cardinals]] κ less than 2<sup>ℵ<sub>1</sub></sup>.
Baumgartner's '''axiom A''' is an axiom for partially ordered sets introduced in {{harv|Baumgartner|1983|loc=section 7}}. A partial order (''P'',&nbsp;≤) is said to satisfy axiom A if there is a family ≤<sub>''n''</sub> of partial orderings on ''P'' for ''n''&nbsp;=&nbsp;0,&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2,&nbsp;... such that # ≤<sub>0</sub> is the same as&nbsp;≤ #If ''p''&nbsp;≤<sub>''n''+1</sub>''q'' then ''p''&nbsp;≤<sub>''n''</sub>''q'' #If there is a sequence ''p''<sub>''n''</sub> with ''p''<sub>''n''+1</sub>&nbsp;≤<sub>''n''</sub> ''p''<sub>''n''</sub> then there is a ''q'' with ''q''&nbsp;≤<sub>''n''</sub> ''p''<sub>''n''</sub> for all ''n''. #If ''I'' is a pairwise incompatible subset of ''P'' then for all ''p'' and for all natural numbers ''n'' there is a ''q'' such that ''q''&nbsp;≤<sub>''n''</sub> ''p'' and the number of elements of ''I'' compatible with ''q'' is countable.
