In mathematics, the '''Conley–Zehnder theorem''', named after [[Charles C. Conley]] and [[Eduard Zehnder]], provides a lower bound for the number of [[fixed point (mathematics)|fixed points]] of [[Hamiltonian vector field|Hamiltonian diffeomorphism]]s of standard symplectic [[torus|tori]] in terms of the topology of the underlying tori. The lower bound is one plus the [[cup-length]] of the torus (thus 2n+1, where 2n is the dimension of the considered torus), and it can be strengthen to the rank of the homology of the torus (which is 2<sup>2n</sup>) provided all the fixed points are non-degenerate, this latter condition being generic in the C<sup>1</sup>-topology.

The theorem was conjectured by [[Vladimir Arnold]], and it was known as the [[Arnold conjecture]] on fixed points of [[symplectomorphism]]s. Its validity was later extended to more general closed symplectic manifolds by [[Andreas Floer]] and several others.

